President Biden addressed over 200 bipartisan mayors during their annual U.S. Conference of Mayors (USCM) Winter Meeting. He highlighted the partnership between his Administration and mayors in tackling crises, rebuilding the economy, and delivering results for working families. The President discussed partnering with cities to implement the American Rescue Plan (ARP) and Bipartisan Infrastructure Law, as well as passing the Build Back Better Act. Ten members of the President's Cabinet, including Secretary of the Treasury Janet Yellen and Attorney General Merrick Garland, spoke at the meeting. The Administration has worked with mayors to distribute personal protective equipment, deploy surge response teams, and increase COVID-19 vaccinations. President Biden has added 6.4 million jobs, with an unemployment rate of 3.9% due to the American Rescue Plan. The Administration has provided resources to expand and improve the workforce development system. The Bipartisan Infrastructure Law will rebuild infrastructure, provide high-speed internet, and support domestic manufacturing. The Administration is working with mayors to address supply chain blockages and advance local climate action. They are also partnering with mayors to reduce gun violence, prevent housing instability and homelessness, and build a fair immigration system. The Administration has welcomed Afghan allies to the U.S. and is working with state and local officials for their resettlement.